03863nam a22006015i 9780292767775DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211979txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927677757 a10.7560/7271822doi  a(DE-B1597)588775  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aDS365b.K32 1979 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a309.1581041 aKakar, Hasan Kawun, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGovernment and Society in Afghanistan :bThe Reign of Amir ‘Abd al-Rahman Khan /cHasan Kawun Kakar. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1979  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Transcription -- tIntroduction -- tChapter I The Central Government: 1 -- tChapter II The Central Government: 2 -- tChapter III The Local Government -- tChapter IV The System of Taxation -- tChapter V The Army -- tChapter VI Social Structure: 1 -- tChapter VII Social Structure: 2 -- tChapter VIII Economic Structure: 1 -- tChapter IX Economic Structure: 2 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNote on Sources -- tNotes -- tAbbreviations Used in the Notes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is an authoritative study of the administrative, social, and economic structure of Afghanistan during a decisive stage in its history. The period covered—the reign of the "Iron" Amir Rahman Khan—was in many ways the beginning of modern Afghanistan as a cohesive nation. Although Afghanistan had emerged as an entity in 1747, it was actually under the Amir that its borders were established, its internal unification completed, and the modern concept of nationhood implanted. Kakar approaches this complex process by taking into consideration both the internal and the external forces that influenced its development. Thus, modernization, centralization, and nationalization are seen as both defensive reactions to European imperialism and necessary preconditions to capital formation and, consequently, industrialization. The first part of the book covers the government of the Amir, from the personality of the ruler down to the operation of his new bureaucrats at the local level. Here Kakar presents a comprehensive treatment of the Afghan system of taxation and local government. The second part views these economic and social institutions from the perspective of the major segments of the populace—nomads, townsmen, tribes, women, slaves, landowners, mullahs, merchants, and so forth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72718240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767775423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767775/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK